      "Cl[Al](Cl)Cl"
    ],
    "rationale": "The Fries rearrangement of phenyl acetate to 2-hydroxyacetophenone is the simplest and most frequently cited textbook example. It clearly demonstrates the migration of an acyl group from a phenolic oxygen to an ortho position on the aromatic ring, which is the defining characteristic of this reaction family. The use of a simple acetyl group and an unsubstituted phenyl ring makes it canonical and easy to parse.",
    "collision_avoidance_note": "This example uses a simple phenyl acetate, avoiding complex polycyclic aromatic systems that could be mistaken for other named reactions involving arenes. It specifically shows an acyl migration, distinguishing it from Claisen rearrangements (allyl migration) or rearrangements involving different functional groups. The reaction is a rearrangement, not a substitution or addition, which helps avoid collisions with reactions like Friedel-Crafts acylation, although the mechanism shares features."
  }
}
